# Auto detect text files and perform LF normalization
* text=auto

# --- Working-tree line endings, pinned (2026-07-21) -------------------------------------------
#
# `text=auto` alone normalises to LF **on commit only**. The checkout side stays platform
# dependent, so on Windows (`core.autocrlf`) a `git checkout` can hand the working tree CRLF
# while git still reports it clean — the difference is invisible to `git status` precisely
# because normalisation happens at commit time.
#
# That split cost three separate agents on 2026-07-21, after a `git checkout -- apps/web`
# rewrote that subtree as CRLF while the rest of the repo stayed LF:
#   * two replay scripts whose exact-match anchors silently stopped matching, on files whose
#     content was byte-identical to HEAD;
#   * `apps/web/src/app/motion.test.ts`, whose regex ends `\n\}\n` and therefore cannot match
#     a block closing `}\r\n`. Exactly 1 test out of 1655 noticed.
#
# Pinning `eol` makes checkout deterministic on every platform, so any assertion that reads a
# file's raw bytes is correct by construction rather than by luck of the developer's OS.
*.ts   text eol=lf
*.tsx  text eol=lf
*.js   text eol=lf
*.mjs  text eol=lf
*.cjs  text eol=lf
*.json text eol=lf
*.css  text eol=lf
*.html text eol=lf
*.md   text eol=lf
*.rs   text eol=lf
*.toml text eol=lf
*.yml  text eol=lf
*.yaml text eol=lf
*.sql  text eol=lf
*.sh   text eol=lf

# Windows batch files are the one genuine exception: `cmd.exe` can mis-parse LF-terminated
# scripts, so these stay CRLF deliberately rather than by platform accident.
*.bat  text eol=crlf
*.cmd  text eol=crlf
